This article is a presidential proclamation issued by Barack Obama on August 4, 2011. It discusses the suspension of entry into the United States for immigrants and nonimmigrants who have participated in serious human rights violations, humanitarian law violations, and other abuses. The proclamation highlights the United States' commitment to respect for human rights and humanitarian law and the need to prevent the country from becoming a safe haven for violators. The purpose of the proclamation is to restrict international travel and entry into the United States for individuals who have engaged in the outlined acts. The Secretary of State is responsible for identifying and implementing the measures outlined in the proclamation. The proclamation is effective immediately and will remain in effect until the Secretary of State determines it is no longer necessary.